    {
      "id": "866acaaa51c42db6d0fcd45f9face114953433d8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2023-04-03 07:13:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nOn the one hand, it makes sense to avoid spurious test failures, so I'm giving this a +1, but this means functionality will not be tested on these systems.  There are two sanity subtests affected, but a lot more in sanity-sec. \n\nIt would be good to add a USER0 definition to your test config file (in lustre/tests/cfg/$NAME.sh) or create the sanityusr on your test nodes so that these tests can be run there.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a0d08db1c08da4479ae8b4ad21222cf93ce59479",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 887,
        "name": "xinliang",
        "email": "xinliang.liu@linaro.org",
        "username": "xinliang.liu"
      },
      "date": "2023-04-03 07:34:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n> \n> On the one hand, it makes sense to avoid spurious test failures, so I'm giving this a +1, but this means functionality will not be tested on these systems.  There are two sanity subtests affected, but a lot more in sanity-sec. \n\nYeah, sanity-sec test suite use USER0/1 too. But it calls id $USER0/1 in the beginning which can check if user USER0/1 existed. So here adding checking for USER0 in sanity is necessary.\n\n> \n> It would be good to add a USER0 definition to your test config file (in lustre/tests/cfg/$NAME.sh) or create the sanityusr on your test nodes so that these tests can be run there.\n\nDone. https://github.com/Linaro/lustretest/commit/cae0193b334c856baceae509651c9f76a537b13f",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
